Inapproximability of Maximum Weighted Edge Biclique and Its Applications

Jinsong Tan
Abstract

Given a bipartite graph G=(V1,V2,E)𝐺subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2𝐸G=(V_{1},V_{2},E) where edges take on both positive and negative weights from set 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}, the maximum weighted edge biclique problem, or 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}-MWEB for short, asks to find a bipartite subgraph whose sum of edge weights is maximized. This problem has various applications in bioinformatics, machine learning and databases and its (in)approximability remains open. In this paper, we show that for a wide range of choices of 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}, specifically when |min⁡𝒮max⁡𝒮|∈Ω​(ηδ−1/2)∩O​(η1/2−δ)𝒮𝒮Ωsuperscript𝜂𝛿12𝑂superscript𝜂12𝛿\left|\frac{\min\mathcal{S}}{\max\mathcal{S}}\right|\in\Omega(\eta^{\delta-1/2})\cap O(\eta^{1/2-\delta}) (where η=max⁡{|V1|,|V2|}𝜂subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2\eta=\max\{|V_{1}|,|V_{2}|\}, and δ∈(0,1/2]𝛿012\delta\in(0,1/2]), no polynomial time algorithm can approximate 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}-MWEB within a factor of nϵsuperscript𝑛italic-ϵn^{\epsilon} for some ϵ>0italic-ϵ0\epsilon>0 unless 𝖱𝖯=𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP=NP}. This hardness result gives justification of the heuristic approaches adopted for various applied problems in the aforementioned areas, and indicates that good approximation algorithms are unlikely to exist. Specifically, we give two applications by showing that: 1) finding statistically significant biclusters in the SAMBA model, proposed in [18] for the analysis of microarray data, is nϵsuperscript𝑛italic-ϵn^{\epsilon}-inapproximable; and 2) no polynomial time algorithm exists for the Minimum Description Length with Holes problem [4] unless 𝖱𝖯=𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP=NP}.

1 Introduction

Let G=(V1,V2,E)𝐺subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2𝐸G=(V_{1},V_{2},E) be an undirected bipartite graph. A biclique subgraph in G𝐺G is a complete bipartite subgraph of G𝐺G and maximum edge biclique (MEB) is the problem of finding a biclique subgraph with the most number of edges. MEB is a well-known problem and received much attention in recent years because of its wide range of applications in areas including machine learning [14], management science [16] and bioinformatics, where it is found particularly relevant in the formulation of numerous biclustering problems for biological data analysis [5, 2, 18, 19, 17], and we refer readers to the survey by Madeira and Oliveira [13] for a fairly extensive discussion on this. Maximum edge biclique is shown to be NP-hard by Peeters [15] via a reduction from 3SAT. Its approximability status, on the other hand, remains an open question despite considerable efforts [7, 8, 12] 111Note it might be easy to confuse the MEB problem with the Bipartite Clique problem discussed by Khot in [12]. Bipartite Clique, which also known as Balanced Complete Bipartite Subgraph [8], aims to maximize the number of vertices of a balanced subgraph whereas MEB aims to maximize the total weights on edges in a (not necessarily balanced) subgraph.. In particular, Feige and Kogan [8] conjectured that maximum edge biclique is hard to approximate within a factor of nϵsuperscript𝑛italic-ϵn^{\epsilon} for some ϵ>0italic-ϵ0\epsilon>0. In this paper, we consider a weighted formulation of this problem defined as follows

Definition 1

𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}-Maximum Weighted Edge Biclique (𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}-MWEB)

Instance: A complete bipartite graph G=(V1,V2,E)𝐺subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2𝐸G=(V_{1},V_{2},E) (throughout the paper, let η=m​a​x​{|V1|,|V2|}𝜂𝑚𝑎𝑥subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2\eta=max\{|V_{1}|,|V_{2}|\} and n=|V1|+|V2|𝑛subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2n=|V_{1}|+|V_{2}|), a weight function wG:E→𝒮:subscript𝑤𝐺→𝐸𝒮w_{G}:E\rightarrow\mathcal{S}, where 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S} is a set consisting of both positive and negative integers.

Question: Find a biclique subgraph of G𝐺G where the sum of weights on edges is maximized.

A few comments are in order. First note it is not a lose of generality but a technical convenience to require the graph be complete, one can always think of an incomplete bipartite graph as complete where non-edges are assigned weight 0. Also note we require that both positive and negative weights be in 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S} at the same time because otherwise 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}-MWEB becomes a trivial problem.

Our study of 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}-MWEB is motivated by the problem of finding statistically significant biclusters in microarray data analysis in the SAMBA model [18] and the Minimum Description Length with Holes (MDLH) problem [3, 4, 10]; detailed discussion of the two problems can be found in Sect. 4. Our main technical contribution of this paper is to show that if 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S} satisfies the condition |min⁡𝒮max⁡𝒮|∈Ω​(ηδ−1/2)∩O​(η1/2−δ)𝒮𝒮Ωsuperscript𝜂𝛿12𝑂superscript𝜂12𝛿|\frac{\min\mathcal{S}}{\max\mathcal{S}}|\in\Omega(\eta^{\delta-1/2})\cap O(\eta^{1/2-\delta}), where δ>0𝛿0\delta>0 is any arbitrarily small constant, then no polynomial time algorithm can approximate 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}-MWEB within a factor of nϵsuperscript𝑛italic-ϵn^{\epsilon} for some ϵ>0italic-ϵ0\epsilon>0 unless 𝖱𝖯=𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP=NP}. This result enables us to answer open questions regarding the hardness of the SAMBA model and the MDLH problem. Since maximum edge biclique can be characterized as a special case of 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}-MWEB with 𝒮={−η,1}𝒮𝜂1\mathcal{S}=\{-\eta,1\}, the nϵsuperscript𝑛italic-ϵn^{\epsilon}-inapproximability result also provides interesting insights into the conjectured nϵsuperscript𝑛italic-ϵn^{\epsilon}-inapproximability [8] of maximum edge biclique.

The rest of the paper is organized in three sections. In Sect. 2, we present the main technical result by proving the aforementioned inapproximability of 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}-MWEB. We give applications of this by answering hardness questions regarding two applied problems in Sect. 3. We conclude this work by raising a few open problems in the last section.

2 Approximating 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S}-Maximum Edge Biclique is Hard

We start this section by giving two lemmas about CLIQUE, which will be used in establishing inapproximability for the biclique problems we consider later. Lemma 1 is a recent result by Zuckerman [20], obtained by a derandomization of results of Håstad [11]; Lemma 2 follows immediately from Lemma 1.

Lemma 1

([20]) It is NP-hard to approximate CLIQUE within a factor of n1−ϵsuperscript𝑛1italic-ϵn^{1-\epsilon}, for any ϵ>0italic-ϵ0\epsilon>0.

Lemma 2

For any constant ϵ>0italic-ϵ0\epsilon>0, no polynomial time algorithm can approximate CLIQUE within a factor of n1−ϵsuperscript𝑛1italic-ϵn^{1-\epsilon} with probability at least 1p​o​l​y​(n)1𝑝𝑜𝑙𝑦𝑛\frac{1}{poly(n)} unless 𝖱𝖯=𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP=NP}.

3 Two Applications

In this section, we describe two applications of the results establish in Sect. 3 by proving hardness and inapproximability of problems found in practice.

3.1 SAMBA Model is Hard

Microarray technology has been the latest technological breakthrough in biological and biomedical research; in many applications, a key step in analyzing gene expression data obtained through microarray is the identification of a bicluster satisfying certain properties and with largest area (see the survey [13] for a fairly extensive discussion on this).

In particular, Tanay et. al. [18] considered the Statistical-Algorithmic Method for Bicluster Analysis (SAMBA) model. In their formulation, a complete bipartite graph is given where one side corresponds to genes and the other size corresponds to conditions. An edges (u,v)𝑢𝑣(u,v) is assigned a real weight which could be either positive or negative, depending on the expression level of gene u𝑢u in condition v𝑣v, in a way such that heavy subgraphs corresponds to statistically significant biclusters. Two weight-assigning schemes are considered in their paper. In the first, or simple statistical model, a tight upper-bound on the probability of an observed biclusters in computed; in the second, or refined statistical model, the weights are assigned in a way such that a maximum weight biclique subgraph corresponds to a maximum likelihood bicluster.

The Simple SAMBA Statistical Model:

Let H=(V1′,V2′,E′)𝐻superscriptsubscript𝑉1′superscriptsubscript𝑉2′superscript𝐸′H=(V_{1}^{\prime},V_{2}^{\prime},E^{\prime}) be a subgraph of G=(V1,V2,E)𝐺subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2𝐸G=(V_{1},V_{2},E), E′¯={V1′×V2′}−E′¯superscript𝐸′superscriptsubscript𝑉1′superscriptsubscript𝑉2′superscript𝐸′\overline{E^{\prime}}=\{V_{1}^{\prime}\times V_{2}^{\prime}\}-E^{\prime} and p=|E||V1|​|V2|𝑝𝐸subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2p=\frac{|E|}{|V_{1}||V_{2}|}. The simple statistical model assumes that edges occur independently and identically at random with probability p𝑝p. Denote by B​T​(k,p,n)𝐵𝑇𝑘𝑝𝑛BT(k,p,n) the probability of observing k𝑘k or more successes in n𝑛n binomial trials, the probability of observing a graph at least as dense as H𝐻H is thus p​(H)=B​T​(|E′|,p,|V1′|​|V2′|)𝑝𝐻𝐵𝑇superscript𝐸′𝑝superscriptsubscript𝑉1′superscriptsubscript𝑉2′p(H)=BT(|E^{\prime}|,p,|V_{1}^{\prime}||V_{2}^{\prime}|). This model assumes p<12𝑝12p<\frac{1}{2} and |V1′|​|V2′|≪|V1|​|V2|much-less-thansuperscriptsubscript𝑉1′superscriptsubscript𝑉2′subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2|V_{1}^{\prime}||V_{2}^{\prime}|\ll|V_{1}||V_{2}|, therefore p​(H)𝑝𝐻p(H) is upper bounded by

p∗​(H)=2|V1′|​|V2′|​p|E′|​(1−p)|V1′|​|V2′|−|E′|superscript𝑝𝐻superscript2superscriptsubscript𝑉1′superscriptsubscript𝑉2′superscript𝑝superscript𝐸′superscript1𝑝superscriptsubscript𝑉1′superscriptsubscript𝑉2′superscript𝐸′p^{*}(H)=2^{|V_{1}^{\prime}||V_{2}^{\prime}|}p^{|E^{\prime}|}(1-p)^{|V_{1}^{\prime}||V_{2}^{\prime}|-|E^{\prime}|}

The goal of this model is thus to find a subgraph H𝐻H with the smallest p∗​(H)superscript𝑝𝐻p^{*}(H). This is equivalent to maximizing

3.2 Minimum Description Length with Holes (MDLH) is Hard

Bu et. al [4] considered the Minimum Description Length with Holes problem (defined in the following); the 2-dimensional case is claimed 𝖭𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{NP}-hard in this paper and the proof is referred to [3]. However, the proof given in [3] suffers from an error in its reduction333In Lemma 3.2.1 of [3], the reduction from CLIQUE to CEW is incorrect., thus whether MDLH is NP-complete remains unsettled. In this section, by employing the results established in the previous sections, we show that no polynomial time algorithm exists for MDLH, under the slightly weaker (than 𝖯≠𝖭𝖯𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{P\neq NP}) but widely believed assumption 𝖱𝖯≠𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP\neq NP}.

We first briefly describe the Minimum Description Length summarization with Holes problem; for a detailed discussion of the subject, we refer the readers to [3, 4].

Suppose one is given a k𝑘k-dimensional binary matrix M𝑀M, where each entry is of value either 1, which is of interest, or of value 0, which is not of interest. Besides, there are also k𝑘k hierarchies (trees) associated with each dimension, namely T1,T2,…,Tksubscript𝑇1subscript𝑇2…subscript𝑇𝑘T_{1},T_{2},...,T_{k}, each of height l1,l2,…,lksubscript𝑙1subscript𝑙2…subscript𝑙𝑘l_{1},l_{2},...,l_{k} respectively. Define l​e​v​e​l𝑙𝑒𝑣𝑒𝑙level l=maxi​(li)𝑙subscriptmax𝑖subscript𝑙𝑖l=\text{max}_{i}(l_{i}). For each Tisubscript𝑇𝑖T_{i}, there is a bijection between its leafs and the ’hyperplanes’ in the i𝑖ith dimension (e.g. in a 2-dimensional matrix, these hyperplanes corresponds to rows and columns). A r​e​g​i​o​n𝑟𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑜𝑛region is a tuple (x1,x2,…,xk)subscript𝑥1subscript𝑥2…subscript𝑥𝑘(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{k}), where xisubscript𝑥𝑖x_{i} is a leaf node or an internal node in hierarchy Tisubscript𝑇𝑖T_{i}. Region (x1,x2,…,xk)subscript𝑥1subscript𝑥2…subscript𝑥𝑘(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{k}) is said to c​o​v​e​r𝑐𝑜𝑣𝑒𝑟cover cell (c1,c2,…,ck)subscript𝑐1subscript𝑐2…subscript𝑐𝑘(c_{1},c_{2},...,c_{k}) if cisubscript𝑐𝑖c_{i} is a descendant of xisubscript𝑥𝑖x_{i}, for all 1≤i≤k1𝑖𝑘1\leq i\leq k. A k𝑘k-dimensional l𝑙l-level MDLH summary is defined as two sets S𝑆S and H𝐻H, where 1) S𝑆S is a set of regions covering all the 1-entries in M𝑀M; and 2) H𝐻H is the set of 0-entries covered (undesirably) by S𝑆S and to be excluded from the summary. The length of a summary is defined as |S|+|H|𝑆𝐻|S|+|H|, and the MDLH problem asks the question if there exists a MDLH summary of length at most K𝐾K, for a given K>0𝐾0K>0.

In an effort to establish hardness of MDLH, we first define the following problem, which serves as an intermediate problem bridging {−1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB and MDLH.

Definition 3

(Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P})
Instance: A complete bipartite graph G=(V1,V2,E)𝐺subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2𝐸G=(V_{1},V_{2},E) where each edge takes on a value in {−1,1}11\{-1,1\}, and a positive integer k𝑘k.

Question: Does there exist an induced subgraph (a biclique U1×U2subscript𝑈1subscript𝑈2U_{1}\times U_{2}) whose total weight of edges is ω𝜔\omega, such that |U1|+|U2|+ω≥ksubscript𝑈1subscript𝑈2𝜔𝑘|U_{1}|+|U_{2}|+\omega\geq k.

Lemma 6

No polynomial time algorithm exists for Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} unless 𝖱𝖯=𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP=NP}.

Proof

We prove this by constructing a reduction from {−1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB to Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} as follows: for the given input biclique G=(V1,V2,E)𝐺subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2𝐸G=(V_{1},V_{2},E), make N𝑁N duplicates of V1subscript𝑉1V_{1} and N𝑁N duplicates of V2subscript𝑉2V_{2}, where N=(|V1|+|V2|)2𝑁superscriptsubscript𝑉1subscript𝑉22N=(|V_{1}|+|V_{2}|)^{2}. Connect each copy of V1subscript𝑉1V_{1} to each copy of V2subscript𝑉2V_{2} in a way that is identical to the input biclique, we then claim that there is a size k𝑘k solution to {−1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB if and only if there is a size N2​ksuperscript𝑁2𝑘N^{2}k solution to Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P}.

If there is a size k𝑘k solution to {−1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB, then it is straightforward that there is a solution to Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} of size at least N2​ksuperscript𝑁2𝑘N^{2}k. For the reverse direction, we show that if no solution to {−1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB is of size at least k𝑘k, then the maximum solution to Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} is strictly less than N2​ksuperscript𝑁2𝑘N^{2}k. Note a solution U1N×U2Nsuperscriptsubscript𝑈1𝑁superscriptsubscript𝑈2𝑁U_{1}^{N}\times U_{2}^{N} to Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} consists of at most N2superscript𝑁2N^{2} (not necessarily all distinct) solutions to {−1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB, and each of them can contribute at most (k−1)𝑘1(k-1) in weight to U1N×U2Nsuperscriptsubscript𝑈1𝑁superscriptsubscript𝑈2𝑁U_{1}^{N}\times U_{2}^{N}, so the total weight gained from edges is at most N2​(k−1)superscript𝑁2𝑘1N^{2}(k-1). And note the total weight gained from vertices is at most N​(|V1|+|V2|)=N​N𝑁subscript𝑉1subscript𝑉2𝑁𝑁N(|V_{1}|+|V_{2}|)=N\sqrt{N}, therefore the weight is upper bounded by N​N+N2​(k−1)<N2​k𝑁𝑁superscript𝑁2𝑘1superscript𝑁2𝑘N\sqrt{N}+N^{2}(k-1)<N^{2}k and this completes the proof.

As a conclusion, we have a polynomial time reduction from {−1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB to Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P}. Since no polynomial time algorithm exists for {−1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB unless 𝖱𝖯=𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP=NP}, the same holds for Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P}. ∎

Theorem 3.3

No polynomial time algorithm exists for MDLH summarization, even in the 2-dimension 2-level case, unless 𝖱𝖯=𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP=NP}.

Proof

We prove this by showing that Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} is a complementary problem of 2-dimensional 2-level MDLH.

Let the input 2D matrix M𝑀M be of size n1×n2subscript𝑛1subscript𝑛2n_{1}\times n_{2}, with a tree of height 2 associated with each dimension. Without loss of generality, we only consider the ’sparse’ case where the number of 1-entries is less than the number of 0-entries by at least 2 so that the optimal solution will never contain the whole matrix as one of its regions. Let S𝑆S be the set of regions in a solution. Let R𝑅R and C𝐶C be the set of rows and columns not included in S𝑆S. Let Z𝑍Z be the set of all zero entries in M𝑀M. Let z𝑧z be the total number of zero entries in the R×C𝑅𝐶R\times C ’leftover’ matrix and let w𝑤w be the total number of 1-entries in it. MDLH tries to minimize the following:

(n1−|R|)+(n2−|C|)+(|Z|−z)+w=(n1+n2+|Z|)−(|R|+|C|+z−w)subscript𝑛1𝑅subscript𝑛2𝐶𝑍𝑧𝑤subscript𝑛1subscript𝑛2𝑍𝑅𝐶𝑧𝑤(n_{1}-|R|)+(n_{2}-|C|)+(|Z|-z)+w=(n_{1}+n_{2}+|Z|)-(|R|+|C|+z-w)

Since (n1+n2+|Z|)subscript𝑛1subscript𝑛2𝑍(n_{1}+n_{2}+|Z|) is a fixed quantity for any given input matrix, the 2-dimensional 2-level MDLH problem is equivalent to maximizing (|R|+|C|+z−w)𝑅𝐶𝑧𝑤(|R|+|C|+z-w), which is precisely the definition of Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P}.

Therefore, 2-dimensional 2-level MDLH is a complementary problem to Problem 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} and by Lemma 6 we conclude that no polynomial time algorithm exists for 2-dimensional 2-level MDLH unless 𝖱𝖯=𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP=NP}. ∎

4 Concluding Remarks

Maximum weighted edge biclique and its variants have received much attention in recently years because of it wide range of applications in various fields including machine learning, database, and particularly bioinformatics and computational biology, where many computational problems for the analysis of microarray data are closely related. To tackle these applied problems, various kinds of heuristics are proposed and experimented and it is not known whether these algorithms give provable approximations. In this work, we answer this question by showing that it is highly unlikely (under the assumption 𝖱𝖯≠𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP\neq NP}) that good polynomial time approximation algorithm exists for maximum weighted edge biclique for a wide range of choices of weight; and we further give specific applications of this result to two applied problems. We conclude our work by listing a few open questions.

1. We have shown that {Θ​(−ηδ),1}Θsuperscript𝜂𝛿1\{\Theta(-\eta^{\delta}),1\}-MWEB is nϵsuperscript𝑛italic-ϵn^{\epsilon}-inapproximable for δ∈(−12,12)𝛿1212\delta\in(-\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{2}); also it is easy to see that (i) the problem is in 𝖯𝖯\mathsf{P} when δ≤−1𝛿1\delta\leq-1, where the entire input graph is the optimal solution; (ii) for any δ≥1𝛿1\delta\geq 1, the problem is equivalent to MEB, which is conjectured to be nϵsuperscript𝑛italic-ϵn^{\epsilon}-inapproximable [8]. Therefore it is natural to ask what is the approximability of the {−nδ,1}superscript𝑛𝛿1\{-n^{\delta},1\}-MWEB problem when δ∈(−1,−12]𝛿112\delta\in(-1,-\frac{1}{2}] and δ∈[12,1]𝛿121\delta\in[\frac{1}{2},1]. In particular, can this be answered by a better analysis of Lemma 3?

2. We are especially interested in {−1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB, which is closely related to the formulations of many natural problems [1, 3, 4, 18]. We have shown that no polynomial time algorithm exists for this problem unless 𝖱𝖯=𝖭𝖯𝖱𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{RP=NP}, and we believe this problem is 𝖭𝖯𝖭𝖯\mathsf{NP}-complete, however a proof has eluded us so far.
